{
  "body": "Generate ONE 360° equirectangular panoramic image (full 360°×180° projection) of:\n\n{{place}}\n\nThis image must be a TRUE equirectangular projection — width:height ratio exactly 2:1, suitable for direct loading into VR viewers, Google Street View, real-estate platforms, or sphere viewers without further conversion.\n\nProjection rules (critical — most equirectangular generations fail here)\n- Aspect ratio strictly 2:1 (1536 × 768 here).\n- Top edge of the image = the zenith (straight up). Bottom edge = the nadir (straight down).\n- The horizon must run as a perfectly horizontal line across the vertical center of the image.\n- Pixels near the top and bottom must be horizontally stretched (the standard equirectangular distortion). Do NOT render the top as a flat ceiling — it must wrap.\n- Left and right edges must seamlessly tile (the right edge continues into the left edge). No visible seam.\n\nScene\n- Type: {{place_type}}\n- Time of day & ambient light: {{time_of_day}}\n- Weather / atmosphere: {{weather}}\n- Render style: {{render_style}}\n\nComposition\n- The viewer's primary focal point (centered horizontally, on the horizon line, facing the camera): {{focal_point}}\n- The space behind the camera (which lands on the left and right edges of the equirectangular image) must be equally finished — do not leave it blank or repetitive.\n- Distribute light sources around the full 360° so the resulting sphere feels balanced (no half-lit panorama).\n\nQuality\n- Crisp detail across the full sphere, including the floor / ground (which gets compressed into the bottom strip) and the ceiling / sky (top strip).\n- No camera tripod or photographer visible at the nadir (the bottom). If a tripod artifact would be there, paint it out cleanly with the surrounding floor.\n- Materials read true-to-life: wood grain, fabric weave, metal reflectivity, glass transparency.\n\nStrict avoid\n- Do NOT output a flat rectangular landscape image labeled as panoramic. It must be a real equirectangular projection with the polar stretching at top and bottom.\n- No visible vertical seam at the wrap-around edges.\n- No people unless explicitly described in {{place}}.\n- No watermark, no text overlay, no compass icon, no UI chrome.\n- No fisheye distortion (fisheye is a different projection — we want equirectangular).\n\n——————\nPlace: {{place}}\nType: {{place_type}}\nTime: {{time_of_day}}\nWeather: {{weather}}\nFocal point: {{focal_point}}\nRender: {{render_style}}\n",
  "community": {
    "author": {
